<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-249  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 249.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 20 1990 v4 n30 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>RCAS rule may stymie call-up of reserves. (the US Army's ReserveComponent Automation System procurement may slow mobilization offorces in Saudi Arabia)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Legislation inserted in US Department of Defense (DOD)appropriations language since 1987 may slow mobilization of ArmyReserve and Army National Guard (ANG) units for duty in SaudiArabia, according to several ANG information management officials.andO;The legislation blocks acquisition of minicomputers ormicrocomputers by the ANG or Army Reserve until the Armyimplements its $1 billion Reserve Component Automation System in1992.andP;  RCAS will deploy 28,000 advanced microcomputers for 5,000mobilization points throughout the US, but until they are ready,ANG officials must rely on Zenith Data Systems Z-248microcomputers now several years old and under-stocked.andP;  ANGofficials say the lack of machines will not affect the units oncethey are in the field; they serve only in administrativecapacities, such as troop addresses and telephone numbers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersEquipment AcquisitionMilitaryLegislationNational GovernmentGovernment ContractsUnited States. Army ReserveUnited States. National Guard.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>